const Q_ENGLISH_2004=[{"id": "objective>English>2004>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I <br/>  <br/> If, once in a lifetime, you see a blue moon, don't think your eyes are playing tricks on you. It's caused by dust in our upper atmosphere; ice crystals are  <br/> what make you see rings round the moon. <br/>  <br/> Over the centuries, magical powers have been attributed to the moon. It has been said to bring on lunacy, affect the growth of plants, eyes of cats, spots of panthers, functions of women and activities of ghosts. France once had a law against cutting timber except during a waning moon. The moon, and to a lesser degree the sun, does cause the ocean tides because of their gravitational pull. But a common mistake of primitive people is to think that everything timed in the same rhythm as the moon is caused by it. <br/>  <br/> All the moon gazing, probing and measuring has never solved the big problem: its origin. One theory is that it began as a planet, got too near the more  <br/> massive earth,was 'captured' and turned into a satellite. Another is that the latter theory is true, scientists say, there would be two clues; the moon  <br/> would consist of lighter material than the earth, and the earth would be left with a scar. As a matter of fact, the moon does weigh less.And the Pacific  <br/> Ocean does have a scarlike bottom of basaltic rocks instead of the granite rocks usually found near the earth's surface. <br/>  <br/> But the assumption that, if man can get to the moon, he'll find the answer is unfounded. Man has been on the earth hundreds of thousands of years without  <br/> determining the earth's origin. Scientists, of course, will never give up either quest. <br/>  <br/> Indeed, for thousands of years the moon has worked a spell of fascination over all the people on its near neighbour, the earth. The ancient worshipped  <br/> this lamp in the sky and speculated about it endlessly. Modern astronomers continue to explore its mysteries almost every night of the year, and with reason. <br/>  <br/> Ages ago, before artificial light was known, it was important as illumination at night. As everyone knows, the moon has no light of its own; it shines  <br/> with the cold reflection of the distant sun, but actually the moon is a poor satellite with 'earth light' sixty times as bright as the best moonlight.  <br/> That's why we sometimes see the whole moon faintly when the sun is lighting up only a narrow crescent. <br/>  <br/> The phrase <em>near neighbour</em>, as used in the passage, shows that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">moonlight generally shares many characteristics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the earth is nearer to the moon than to the sun</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the earth actually shares boundaries with the moon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Moonlight shines brighter on  the earth's</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'near neighbour' in the passage is used to describe the relationship between the moon and the earth. It suggests that the moon is close to the earth, but not in a literal sense of sharing boundaries. Rather, it is used to indicate that the moon is the closest celestial body to the earth. Therefore, the correct option is 'the earth is nearer to the moon than to the sun' because it accurately reflects the meaning of the phrase 'near neighbour' as used in the passage.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I <br/>  <br/> If, once in a lifetime, you see a blue moon, don't think your eyes are playing tricks on you. It's caused by dust in our upper atmosphere; ice crystals are  <br/> what make you see rings round the moon. <br/>  <br/> Over the centuries, magical powers have been attributed to the moon. It has been said to bring on lunacy, affect the growth of plants, eyes of cats, spots of panthers, functions of women and activities of ghosts. France once had a law against cutting timber except during a waning moon. The moon, and to a lesser degree the sun, does cause the ocean tides because of their gravitational pull. But a common mistake of primitive people is to think that everything timed in the same rhythm as the moon is caused by it. <br/>  <br/> All the moon gazing, probing and measuring has never solved the big problem: its origin. One theory is that it began as a planet, got too near the more  <br/> massive earth,was 'captured' and turned into a satellite. Another is that the latter theory is true, scientists say, there would be two clues; the moon  <br/> would consist of lighter material than the earth, and the earth would be left with a scar. As a matter of fact, the moon does weigh less.And the Pacific  <br/> Ocean does have a scarlike bottom of basaltic rocks instead of the granite rocks usually found near the earth's surface. <br/>  <br/> But the assumption that, if man can get to the moon, he'll find the answer is unfounded. Man has been on the earth hundreds of thousands of years without  <br/> determining the earth's origin. Scientists, of course, will never give up either quest. <br/>  <br/> Indeed, for thousands of years the moon has worked a spell of fascination over all the people on its near neighbour, the earth. The ancient worshipped  <br/> this lamp in the sky and speculated about it endlessly. Modern astronomers continue to explore its mysteries almost every night of the year, and with reason. <br/>  <br/> Ages ago, before artificial light was known, it was important as illumination at night. As everyone knows, the moon has no light of its own; it shines  <br/> with the cold reflection of the distant sun, but actually the moon is a poor satellite with 'earth light' sixty times as bright as the best moonlight.  <br/> That's why we sometimes see the whole moon faintly when the sun is lighting up only a narrow crescent. <br/> The passage suggests that a blue moon is a</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rare phenomenon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">regular event</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trick of the moon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">life-long opportunity</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'once in a lifetime' in the passage suggests that seeing a blue moon is a rare occurrence. Therefore, the correct answer is 'rare phenomenon'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I <br/>  <br/> If, once in a lifetime, you see a blue moon, don't think your eyes are playing tricks on you. It's caused by dust in our upper atmosphere; ice crystals are  <br/> what make you see rings round the moon. <br/>  <br/> Over the centuries, magical powers have been attributed to the moon. It has been said to bring on lunacy, affect the growth of plants, eyes of cats, spots of panthers, functions of women and activities of ghosts. France once had a law against cutting timber except during a waning moon. The moon, and to a lesser degree the sun, does cause the ocean tides because of their gravitational pull. But a common mistake of primitive people is to think that everything timed in the same rhythm as the moon is caused by it. <br/>  <br/> All the moon gazing, probing and measuring has never solved the big problem: its origin. One theory is that it began as a planet, got too near the more  <br/> massive earth,was 'captured' and turned into a satellite. Another is that the latter theory is true, scientists say, there would be two clues; the moon  <br/> would consist of lighter material than the earth, and the earth would be left with a scar. As a matter of fact, the moon does weigh less.And the Pacific  <br/> Ocean does have a scarlike bottom of basaltic rocks instead of the granite rocks usually found near the earth's surface. <br/>  <br/> But the assumption that, if man can get to the moon, he'll find the answer is unfounded. Man has been on the earth hundreds of thousands of years without  <br/> determining the earth's origin. Scientists, of course, will never give up either quest. <br/>  <br/> Indeed, for thousands of years the moon has worked a spell of fascination over all the people on its near neighbour, the earth. The ancient worshipped  <br/> this lamp in the sky and speculated about it endlessly. Modern astronomers continue to explore its mysteries almost every night of the year, and with reason. <br/>  <br/> Ages ago, before artificial light was known, it was important as illumination at night. As everyone knows, the moon has no light of its own; it shines  <br/> with the cold reflection of the distant sun, but actually the moon is a poor satellite with 'earth light' sixty times as bright as the best moonlight.  <br/> That's why we sometimes see the whole moon faintly when the sun is lighting up only a narrow crescent. <br/> The sentence <em>over the centuries, magical powers have been attributed to the moon</em> suggests that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">people perform magic with the moon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is a common belief that the moon has magical powers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the moon actually possesses magical powers.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The moon  reflects magical powers from the sun's</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'magical powers have been attributed to the moon' suggests that people have believed or assigned magical powers to the moon over the centuries. It does not imply that the moon actually possesses these powers or that people perform magic with the moon. Therefore, the correct answer is 'it is a common belief that the moon has magical powers'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I <br/>  <br/> If, once in a lifetime, you see a blue moon, don't think your eyes are playing tricks on you. It's caused by dust in our upper atmosphere; ice crystals are  <br/> what make you see rings round the moon. <br/>  <br/> Over the centuries, magical powers have been attributed to the moon. It has been said to bring on lunacy, affect the growth of plants, eyes of cats, spots of panthers, functions of women and activities of ghosts. France once had a law against cutting timber except during a waning moon. The moon, and to a lesser degree the sun, does cause the ocean tides because of their gravitational pull. But a common mistake of primitive people is to think that everything timed in the same rhythm as the moon is caused by it. <br/>  <br/> All the moon gazing, probing and measuring has never solved the big problem: its origin. One theory is that it began as a planet, got too near the more  <br/> massive earth,was 'captured' and turned into a satellite. Another is that the latter theory is true, scientists say, there would be two clues; the moon  <br/> would consist of lighter material than the earth, and the earth would be left with a scar. As a matter of fact, the moon does weigh less.And the Pacific  <br/> Ocean does have a scarlike bottom of basaltic rocks instead of the granite rocks usually found near the earth's surface. <br/>  <br/> But the assumption that, if man can get to the moon, he'll find the answer is unfounded. Man has been on the earth hundreds of thousands of years without  <br/> determining the earth's origin. Scientists, of course, will never give up either quest. <br/>  <br/> Indeed, for thousands of years the moon has worked a spell of fascination over all the people on its near neighbour, the earth. The ancient worshipped  <br/> this lamp in the sky and speculated about it endlessly. Modern astronomers continue to explore its mysteries almost every night of the year, and with reason. <br/>  <br/> Ages ago, before artificial light was known, it was important as illumination at night. As everyone knows, the moon has no light of its own; it shines  <br/> with the cold reflection of the distant sun, but actually the moon is a poor satellite with 'earth light' sixty times as bright as the best moonlight.  <br/> That's why we sometimes see the whole moon faintly when the sun is lighting up only a narrow crescent. <br/> The expression <em>either quest</em> refers to the origin of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the moon or the earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">neither the moon nor the earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the moon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the earth</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'either quest' in the context of the passage refers to the ongoing scientific pursuit to understand the origins of both the moon and the earth. The passage discusses theories about the origins of the moon and also mentions that man has been on earth for hundreds of thousands of years without determining the earth's origin. Therefore, the 'either quest' refers to the origin of 'the moon or the earth'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I <br/>  <br/> If, once in a lifetime, you see a blue moon, don't think your eyes are playing tricks on you. It's caused by dust in our upper atmosphere; ice crystals are  <br/> what make you see rings round the moon. <br/>  <br/> Over the centuries, magical powers have been attributed to the moon. It has been said to bring on lunacy, affect the growth of plants, eyes of cats, spots of panthers, functions of women and activities of ghosts. France once had a law against cutting timber except during a waning moon. The moon, and to a lesser degree the sun, does cause the ocean tides because of their gravitational pull. But a common mistake of primitive people is to think that everything timed in the same rhythm as the moon is caused by it. <br/>  <br/> All the moon gazing, probing and measuring has never solved the big problem: its origin. One theory is that it began as a planet, got too near the more  <br/> massive earth,was 'captured' and turned into a satellite. Another is that the latter theory is true, scientists say, there would be two clues; the moon  <br/> would consist of lighter material than the earth, and the earth would be left with a scar. As a matter of fact, the moon does weigh less.And the Pacific  <br/> Ocean does have a scarlike bottom of basaltic rocks instead of the granite rocks usually found near the earth's surface. <br/>  <br/> But the assumption that, if man can get to the moon, he'll find the answer is unfounded. Man has been on the earth hundreds of thousands of years without  <br/> determining the earth's origin. Scientists, of course, will never give up either quest. <br/>  <br/> Indeed, for thousands of years the moon has worked a spell of fascination over all the people on its near neighbour, the earth. The ancient worshipped  <br/> this lamp in the sky and speculated about it endlessly. Modern astronomers continue to explore its mysteries almost every night of the year, and with reason. <br/>  <br/> Ages ago, before artificial light was known, it was important as illumination at night. As everyone knows, the moon has no light of its own; it shines  <br/> with the cold reflection of the distant sun, but actually the moon is a poor satellite with 'earth light' sixty times as bright as the best moonlight.  <br/> That's why we sometimes see the whole moon faintly when the sun is lighting up only a narrow crescent. <br/> A suitable title for the passage is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Magical Powers of the Moon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Facts about the Moon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Lunar Cycle</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Moon-Gazing</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage discusses various aspects of the moon, including its physical characteristics, its effects, theories about its origin, and its role in human history and culture. Therefore, a suitable title for the passage would be 'Facts about the Moon', as it encompasses all the different topics discussed in the passage.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/>  <br/> ...1... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">attorneys </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">determiners </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">antagonists </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protagonists</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'protagonists'. In the context of the passage, the term 'protagonists' refers to the supporters or advocates of capitalism. The passage is discussing the views of those who support capitalism, hence the term 'protagonists' is the most appropriate choice.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...2... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">freedom </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">manoeuvring </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">manipulation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exploitation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'freedom'. The passage is discussing the characteristics of capitalism, and one of the key features of capitalism is economic freedom. This refers to the freedom of producers to produce whatever goods they want and the freedom of consumers to buy whatever they want. Therefore, 'freedom' is the most appropriate choice for the gap.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...3... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">manufactures </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">buys </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sells </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fancies</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the producer is free to produce whatever goods he sells. The term 'sells' is appropriate because it refers to the act of giving something in return for money, which is what a producer does in a capitalist economy.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...4... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">consumer </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">customer </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marketer </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">controller</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the term 'consumer' is the most appropriate. A consumer is a person who purchases goods and services for personal use. In a capitalist economy, the consumer is free to buy what he wants. The other options do not fit into the context of the passage.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...5... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">neutralize </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">decide </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">harmonize </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">settle</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'neutralize'. In the context of the passage, the market mechanism in a capitalist system is described as something that balances or 'neutralizes' the whims and caprice of both the producer and the consumer. This means it ensures that neither the producer nor the consumer can unduly influence the market to their advantage.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...6...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">controlling </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">production </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">operational </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">market</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'market'. The passage is discussing the market mechanism in a capitalist system. This mechanism is what brings the producer and consumer together, determines prices, and distributes resources. Therefore, the term 'market mechanism' fits best in the context.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...7... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">profit </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">output </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dividends </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interest</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the term that fits best in the gap marked ...7... is 'profit'. This is because the passage is discussing the distribution of the total earnings from the production and sale of goods, which is typically referred to as 'profit' in economic terms. 'Output', 'dividends', and 'interest' do not fit in this context as they refer to different aspects of economics. 'Output' refers to the amount of goods produced, 'dividends' are a portion of a company's earnings distributed to shareholders, and 'interest' is the cost of borrowing money.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...8... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">factors </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">methods </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">managers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">agents</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the term that fits best in the gap marked ...8... is 'factors'. This is because the passage is discussing the four recognized contributors to production in economics, which are typically referred to as 'factors' of production. These are land, labour, capital, and organization. 'Methods', 'managers', and 'agents' do not fit in this context as they refer to different aspects of economics and business.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...9...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pricing </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">buyers and sellers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">managers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">operations </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the '...9...' refers to the market mechanism that determines prices and distribution of resources. This mechanism is often referred to as 'pricing'. The pricing mechanism in a capitalist economy is determined by the forces of supply and demand. Therefore, the correct answer is 'pricing'.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Choose the most appropriate option for each gap.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> Capitalism is an economic system which is founded on the principle of free enterprise and the private ownership of the means of production and distribution.  The ...1... of capitalism claim that its essential characteristic is economic ...2... <br/>  The producer is free to produce whatever goods he ...3... ; but the ...4... is equally free to buy what he wants. There is a market mechanism under this system which brings the producer and consumer together and tends to equate the supplies of the one  to the demands of the other, and ...5... the whims and caprice of both. It is this same ...6... mechanism which determines what prices the consumers pay to the producers, as well as what share the total ...7... , in cash or kind, goes to each of the four recognized ...8... of production-land, labour, capital and organization. <br/>  <br/> It is further claimed for this system that every person is capable of watching his or her own interest, and that whatever injustice is done by  <br/> the ...9... of the market mechanism, this mechanism tends to bring about a state of ...10.... <br/> ...10...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equilibrium </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equidistance </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opprobrium </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conflict </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The '...10...' in the passage refers to the state that the market mechanism tends to bring about. In the context of economics, this state is often referred to as 'equilibrium'. Equilibrium is a state in which market supply and demand balance each other, and as a result, prices become stable. Therefore, the correct answer is 'equilibrium'.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE III <br/>  <br/> We knew early in our life that the atmosphere in our home was different from that in many other homes, where husbands and wives quarrel and where there  <br/> was drunkenness,laziness or indifference things we never saw in our family. We chafed and grumbled at the strictness of my father's regime. We went  <br/> to hide whenever we broke the rules too visibly. We knew,nevertheless, that our parents wanted good things for us. Some of these, such as the insistence  <br/> on our going to school and never missing a day, we accepted readily enough, although, like most other children, we occasionally yielded to the temptation  <br/> to play truant. However, in other cases such as their effort to keep us out of contact with the difficult life, the drinking and fighting and beer-brewing  <br/> and gambling their failure was inevitable. They could not keep us insulated. By the time we moved about, we were already seeing things with their eyes  <br/> and judging things by the standards we had absorbed from them. <br/>  <br/> It was borne in me and my brother at a very age that our father was an uncommon man. For one thing, in most African families, work around the home  <br/> was women's work. So we were vastly impressed by the fact that whenever my mother was away, my father could and did do all her jobs cooking, cleaning  <br/> and looking after us. We lived in this way in a community in which housework was regarded as being beneath male dignity. Even in families which, like ours,  <br/> produced boy after boy our sister came fifth it simply meant that the mother carried a greater and greater burden of work. In our family, nevertheless  <br/> the boys did girl's work and my father did it with us. <br/>  <br/> One of the prime chores of life in the family was fetching water from the pump down the street, some two hundred metres from our door. Since the pump was  <br/> not unlocked until six in the morning and there was always crowding, a system had developed whereby you got out before dawn, placed your twenty-litre tin  <br/> in line, and then went home, returning later to take your place. Often, of course, tins would be moved back in line and others moved ahead. This could be  <br/> corrected if none of those in front were too big a challenge. <br/>  <br/> When taps were substituted for the pumps, the first one installed was nearly a kilometre away from our house and we had to make the trek with the water tins balanced on our heads - and indignity because this was the way girls, not proud males, carried their burdens. All the children in the neighbourhood knew we did women's work and I can still hear their derisive  laughter. We did our jobs doggedly, that notwithstanding, because our father and mother expected it of us. Out of choice our father did everything we did, including fetching water on the occasion, and commanded us by sheer force of his example. <br/>  <br/> By describing his father as an uncommon man, the writer means that he is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">amenable  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">remarkable    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">strict   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">kind</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This can be seen in the 2nd paragraph. The writer shows remarkable difference between his father and other men.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE III <br/>  <br/> We knew early in our life that the atmosphere in our home was different from that in many other homes, where husbands and wives quarrel and where there  <br/> was drunkenness,laziness or indifference things we never saw in our family. We chafed and grumbled at the strictness of my father's regime. We went  <br/> to hide whenever we broke the rules too visibly. We knew,nevertheless, that our parents wanted good things for us. Some of these, such as the insistence  <br/> on our going to school and never missing a day, we accepted readily enough, although, like most other children, we occasionally yielded to the temptation  <br/> to play truant. However, in other cases such as their effort to keep us out of contact with the difficult life, the drinking and fighting and beer-brewing  <br/> and gambling their failure was inevitable. They could not keep us insulated. By the time we moved about, we were already seeing things with their eyes  <br/> and judging things by the standards we had absorbed from them. <br/>  <br/> It was borne in me and my brother at a very age that our father was an uncommon man. For one thing, in most African families, work around the home  <br/> was women's work. So we were vastly impressed by the fact that whenever my mother was away, my father could and did do all her jobs cooking, cleaning  <br/> and looking after us. We lived in this way in a community in which housework was regarded as being beneath male dignity. Even in families which, like ours,  <br/> produced boy after boy our sister came fifth it simply meant that the mother carried a greater and greater burden of work. In our family, nevertheless  <br/> the boys did girl's work and my father did it with us. <br/>  <br/> One of the prime chores of life in the family was fetching water from the pump down the street, some two hundred metres from our door. Since the pump was  <br/> not unlocked until six in the morning and there was always crowding, a system had developed whereby you got out before dawn, placed your twenty-litre tin  <br/> in line, and then went home, returning later to take your place. Often, of course, tins would be moved back in line and others moved ahead. This could be  <br/> corrected if none of those in front were too big a challenge. <br/>  <br/> When taps were substituted for the pumps, the first one installed was nearly a kilometre away from our house and we had to make the trek with the water tins balanced on our heads - and indignity because this was the way girls, not proud males, carried their burdens. All the children in the neighbourhood knew we did women's work and I can still hear their derisive  laughter. We did our jobs doggedly, that notwithstanding, because our father and mother expected it of us. Out of choice our father did everything we did, including fetching water on the occasion, and commanded us by sheer force of his example. <br/> Which of the following describes the father's role in the family?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Being too hard on the children</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Usurping his wife's role in the family</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Serving the children</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Leading by example</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The father's role in the family, as described in the passage, is one of leading by example. He does not shy away from doing tasks typically assigned to women, and he expects his children to do the same. This is best represented by option 4.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE III <br/>  <br/> We knew early in our life that the atmosphere in our home was different from that in many other homes, where husbands and wives quarrel and where there  <br/> was drunkenness,laziness or indifference things we never saw in our family. We chafed and grumbled at the strictness of my father's regime. We went  <br/> to hide whenever we broke the rules too visibly. We knew,nevertheless, that our parents wanted good things for us. Some of these, such as the insistence  <br/> on our going to school and never missing a day, we accepted readily enough, although, like most other children, we occasionally yielded to the temptation  <br/> to play truant. However, in other cases such as their effort to keep us out of contact with the difficult life, the drinking and fighting and beer-brewing  <br/> and gambling their failure was inevitable. They could not keep us insulated. By the time we moved about, we were already seeing things with their eyes  <br/> and judging things by the standards we had absorbed from them. <br/>  <br/> It was borne in me and my brother at a very age that our father was an uncommon man. For one thing, in most African families, work around the home  <br/> was women's work. So we were vastly impressed by the fact that whenever my mother was away, my father could and did do all her jobs cooking, cleaning  <br/> and looking after us. We lived in this way in a community in which housework was regarded as being beneath male dignity. Even in families which, like ours,  <br/> produced boy after boy our sister came fifth it simply meant that the mother carried a greater and greater burden of work. In our family, nevertheless  <br/> the boys did girl's work and my father did it with us. <br/>  <br/> One of the prime chores of life in the family was fetching water from the pump down the street, some two hundred metres from our door. Since the pump was  <br/> not unlocked until six in the morning and there was always crowding, a system had developed whereby you got out before dawn, placed your twenty-litre tin  <br/> in line, and then went home, returning later to take your place. Often, of course, tins would be moved back in line and others moved ahead. This could be  <br/> corrected if none of those in front were too big a challenge. <br/>  <br/> When taps were substituted for the pumps, the first one installed was nearly a kilometre away from our house and we had to make the trek with the water tins balanced on our heads - and indignity because this was the way girls, not proud males, carried their burdens. All the children in the neighbourhood knew we did women's work and I can still hear their derisive  laughter. We did our jobs doggedly, that notwithstanding, because our father and mother expected it of us. Out of choice our father did everything we did, including fetching water on the occasion, and commanded us by sheer force of his example. <br/> The word atmosphere, as used in the first paragraph of the passage, means</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pattern   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disposition  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">preference   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unity</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'atmosphere' in the context of the passage refers to the general mood, environment or 'pattern' of behavior and interaction in the family home. It describes the overall feeling or climate in the home, which was different from many other homes where there was quarreling, drunkenness, laziness or indifference. The options 'disposition', 'preference' and 'unity' do not accurately capture this meaning.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE III <br/>  <br/> We knew early in our life that the atmosphere in our home was different from that in many other homes, where husbands and wives quarrel and where there  <br/> was drunkenness,laziness or indifference things we never saw in our family. We chafed and grumbled at the strictness of my father's regime. We went  <br/> to hide whenever we broke the rules too visibly. We knew,nevertheless, that our parents wanted good things for us. Some of these, such as the insistence  <br/> on our going to school and never missing a day, we accepted readily enough, although, like most other children, we occasionally yielded to the temptation  <br/> to play truant. However, in other cases such as their effort to keep us out of contact with the difficult life, the drinking and fighting and beer-brewing  <br/> and gambling their failure was inevitable. They could not keep us insulated. By the time we moved about, we were already seeing things with their eyes  <br/> and judging things by the standards we had absorbed from them. <br/>  <br/> It was borne in me and my brother at a very age that our father was an uncommon man. For one thing, in most African families, work around the home  <br/> was women's work. So we were vastly impressed by the fact that whenever my mother was away, my father could and did do all her jobs cooking, cleaning  <br/> and looking after us. We lived in this way in a community in which housework was regarded as being beneath male dignity. Even in families which, like ours,  <br/> produced boy after boy our sister came fifth it simply meant that the mother carried a greater and greater burden of work. In our family, nevertheless  <br/> the boys did girl's work and my father did it with us. <br/>  <br/> One of the prime chores of life in the family was fetching water from the pump down the street, some two hundred metres from our door. Since the pump was  <br/> not unlocked until six in the morning and there was always crowding, a system had developed whereby you got out before dawn, placed your twenty-litre tin  <br/> in line, and then went home, returning later to take your place. Often, of course, tins would be moved back in line and others moved ahead. This could be  <br/> corrected if none of those in front were too big a challenge. <br/>  <br/> When taps were substituted for the pumps, the first one installed was nearly a kilometre away from our house and we had to make the trek with the water tins balanced on our heads - and indignity because this was the way girls, not proud males, carried their burdens. All the children in the neighbourhood knew we did women's work and I can still hear their derisive  laughter. We did our jobs doggedly, that notwithstanding, because our father and mother expected it of us. Out of choice our father did everything we did, including fetching water on the occasion, and commanded us by sheer force of his example. <br/> Which of the following statements captures the family's approach to housework?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">No job was reserved for anyone on the basis of gender</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Their mother did the cooking and cleaning</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The boys were not allowed to do girls work</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The water needed was provided by everyone</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage clearly states that in the family, 'the boys did girl's work and my father did it with us.' This indicates that no job was reserved for anyone on the basis of gender. The other options are not supported by the passage. Their mother did not do all the cooking and cleaning, the boys were not prevented from doing 'girls' work', and the passage does not state that everyone provided the water needed.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p>  <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE III <br/>  <br/> We knew early in our life that the atmosphere in our home was different from that in many other homes, where husbands and wives quarrel and where there  <br/> was drunkenness,laziness or indifference things we never saw in our family. We chafed and grumbled at the strictness of my father's regime. We went  <br/> to hide whenever we broke the rules too visibly. We knew,nevertheless, that our parents wanted good things for us. Some of these, such as the insistence  <br/> on our going to school and never missing a day, we accepted readily enough, although, like most other children, we occasionally yielded to the temptation  <br/> to play truant. However, in other cases such as their effort to keep us out of contact with the difficult life, the drinking and fighting and beer-brewing  <br/> and gambling their failure was inevitable. They could not keep us insulated. By the time we moved about, we were already seeing things with their eyes  <br/> and judging things by the standards we had absorbed from them. <br/>  <br/> It was borne in me and my brother at a very age that our father was an uncommon man. For one thing, in most African families, work around the home  <br/> was women's work. So we were vastly impressed by the fact that whenever my mother was away, my father could and did do all her jobs cooking, cleaning  <br/> and looking after us. We lived in this way in a community in which housework was regarded as being beneath male dignity. Even in families which, like ours,  <br/> produced boy after boy our sister came fifth it simply meant that the mother carried a greater and greater burden of work. In our family, nevertheless  <br/> the boys did girl's work and my father did it with us. <br/>  <br/> One of the prime chores of life in the family was fetching water from the pump down the street, some two hundred metres from our door. Since the pump was  <br/> not unlocked until six in the morning and there was always crowding, a system had developed whereby you got out before dawn, placed your twenty-litre tin  <br/> in line, and then went home, returning later to take your place. Often, of course, tins would be moved back in line and others moved ahead. This could be  <br/> corrected if none of those in front were too big a challenge. <br/>  <br/> When taps were substituted for the pumps, the first one installed was nearly a kilometre away from our house and we had to make the trek with the water tins balanced on our heads - and indignity because this was the way girls, not proud males, carried their burdens. All the children in the neighbourhood knew we did women's work and I can still hear their derisive  laughter. We did our jobs doggedly, that notwithstanding, because our father and mother expected it of us. Out of choice our father did everything we did, including fetching water on the occasion, and commanded us by sheer force of his example. <br/> A suitable title for the passage is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A Village Life         </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Unusual Parent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Problem of Water    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An Experience in Early life</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is about the author's father who was different from other men in their community. He did not conform to the societal norms of their community where housework was considered women's work. Instead, he shared the chores with his wife and children, setting an example for them. Therefore, the title 'The Unusual Parent' is the most suitable as it captures the essence of the passage.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> A Wolf, seeing a Lamb drinking from a river, wanted to find a pretext for devouring him. He stood higher up the stream and accused the lamb of muddying  <br/> the water so that he could not drink. The lamb said that he drank only with tip of his tongue, and that in any case he was standing lower down the river,  <br/> and could not possibly disturb the water higher up. When this excuse failed him, the wolf said: 'Well, last year you insulted my father.' 'I wasn't even  <br/> born then,' replied the lamb. <br/>  <br/> You are good at finding answers, 'said the wolf, 'but what do you mean by taking up so much of the path where I am walking? The lamb, frightened at the wolf's  <br/> angry tone and terrible aspect, told him, with all due submission, that he could not conceive how his walking on such a wide path could occasion him  <br/> inconvenience. 'What!' exclaimed the wolf, seemingly in great anger and indignation. 'You are as impudent as your father who seized me by the throat  <br/> last year, and caused me to be kept in a cage for three months. <br/>  <br/> If you will believe me,' said the lamb, 'my parents are simple creatures who live entirely by green stuff; we are none of us hunters of your species.' 'Ah! I see it's no use talking to you, 'said the wolf, drawing up close to him. 'It runs in the blood of your family to hate us wolves, and therefore, as we have come so conveniently together, I'll just pay off a few of your forefathers' scores before we part. 'So saying, he leapt at the lamb from behind and garroted him. <br/>  <br/> The charges levelled against the lamb are</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pollution, insolence, obstruction and aggression</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exuberance, pollution, wickedness and stubbornness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">garrulity, loquacity, pride and arrogance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">greed, wandering, insolence and disrespect</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pollution and Insolence can be seen in the 1st paragraph. Obstruction and Aggression can be seen in the 2nd paragraph.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> A Wolf, seeing a Lamb drinking from a river, wanted to find a pretext for devouring him. He stood higher up the stream and accused the lamb of muddying  <br/> the water so that he could not drink. The lamb said that he drank only with tip of his tongue, and that in any case he was standing lower down the river,  <br/> and could not possibly disturb the water higher up. When this excuse failed him, the wolf said: 'Well, last year you insulted my father.' 'I wasn't even  <br/> born then,' replied the lamb. <br/>  <br/> You are good at finding answers, 'said the wolf, 'but what do you mean by taking up so much of the path where I am walking? The lamb, frightened at the wolf's  <br/> angry tone and terrible aspect, told him, with all due submission, that he could not conceive how his walking on such a wide path could occasion him  <br/> inconvenience. 'What!' exclaimed the wolf, seemingly in great anger and indignation. 'You are as impudent as your father who seized me by the throat  <br/> last year, and caused me to be kept in a cage for three months. <br/>  <br/> If you will believe me,' said the lamb, 'my parents are simple creatures who live entirely by green stuff; we are none of us hunters of your species.' 'Ah! I see it's no use talking to you, 'said the wolf, drawing up close to him. 'It runs in the blood of your family to hate us wolves, and therefore, as we have come so conveniently together, I'll just pay off a few of your forefathers' scores before we part. 'So saying, he leapt at the lamb from behind and garroted him.  <br/> From the way the story ended, it can be concluded that the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wolf and the lamb parted amicably</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lamb did not survive the encounter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wolf had encountered the lamb's parents</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lamb offended the wolf quite seriously</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the passage, it is clear that the wolf had been looking for a pretext to devour the lamb. Despite the lamb's attempts to reason with the wolf, the wolf ends up attacking and killing the lamb. This is evident from the line 'So saying, he leapt at the lamb from behind and garroted him.' Therefore, the correct answer is that the lamb did not survive the encounter.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> A Wolf, seeing a Lamb drinking from a river, wanted to find a pretext for devouring him. He stood higher up the stream and accused the lamb of muddying  <br/> the water so that he could not drink. The lamb said that he drank only with tip of his tongue, and that in any case he was standing lower down the river,  <br/> and could not possibly disturb the water higher up. When this excuse failed him, the wolf said: 'Well, last year you insulted my father.' 'I wasn't even  <br/> born then,' replied the lamb. <br/>  <br/> You are good at finding answers, 'said the wolf, 'but what do you mean by taking up so much of the path where I am walking? The lamb, frightened at the wolf's  <br/> angry tone and terrible aspect, told him, with all due submission, that he could not conceive how his walking on such a wide path could occasion him  <br/> inconvenience. 'What!' exclaimed the wolf, seemingly in great anger and indignation. 'You are as impudent as your father who seized me by the throat  <br/> last year, and caused me to be kept in a cage for three months. <br/>  <br/> If you will believe me,' said the lamb, 'my parents are simple creatures who live entirely by green stuff; we are none of us hunters of your species.' 'Ah! I see it's no use talking to you, 'said the wolf, drawing up close to him. 'It runs in the blood of your family to hate us wolves, and therefore, as we have come so conveniently together, I'll just pay off a few of your forefathers' scores before we part. 'So saying, he leapt at the lamb from behind and garroted him.  <br/> Which of the following aptly describes the moral of the story?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">No matter how highly placed he is in society,the unmindful lawbreaker will always meet his nemesis</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The law is weak in defence of the poor against the rich and mighty</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sins of the forefathers are visited upon the children</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If you have made up your mind to hang your dog, any rope will do for the purpose</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The moral of the story is that if someone has made up their mind to harm another, they will find any excuse to do so. This is evident from the wolf's behavior in the story. Despite the lamb's attempts to reason with the wolf, the wolf keeps coming up with new accusations and eventually attacks the lamb. This is reflected in the saying 'If you have made up your mind to hang your dog, any rope will do for the purpose', which means that if someone is determined to punish or harm another, they will find any reason to justify their actions.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> A Wolf, seeing a Lamb drinking from a river, wanted to find a pretext for devouring him. He stood higher up the stream and accused the lamb of muddying  <br/> the water so that he could not drink. The lamb said that he drank only with tip of his tongue, and that in any case he was standing lower down the river,  <br/> and could not possibly disturb the water higher up. When this excuse failed him, the wolf said: 'Well, last year you insulted my father.' 'I wasn't even  <br/> born then,' replied the lamb. <br/>  <br/> You are good at finding answers, 'said the wolf, 'but what do you mean by taking up so much of the path where I am walking? The lamb, frightened at the wolf's  <br/> angry tone and terrible aspect, told him, with all due submission, that he could not conceive how his walking on such a wide path could occasion him  <br/> inconvenience. 'What!' exclaimed the wolf, seemingly in great anger and indignation. 'You are as impudent as your father who seized me by the throat  <br/> last year, and caused me to be kept in a cage for three months. <br/>  <br/> If you will believe me,' said the lamb, 'my parents are simple creatures who live entirely by green stuff; we are none of us hunters of your species.' 'Ah! I see it's no use talking to you, 'said the wolf, drawing up close to him. 'It runs in the blood of your family to hate us wolves, and therefore, as we have come so conveniently together, I'll just pay off a few of your forefathers' scores before we part. 'So saying, he leapt at the lamb from behind and garroted him.  <br/> The expression <em>when this excuse failed him</em> suggests that the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lamb was prepared for the charges levelled against</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wolf was uncertain of the charges levelled against the lamb</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wolf only made up the charges levelled against him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lamb was more intelligent than the wolf</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'when this excuse failed him' suggests that the wolf was making up charges against the lamb. The wolf was trying to find a pretext to devour the lamb, and when one excuse didn't work, he moved on to another. This indicates that the charges were fabricated, not based on actual events or actions of the lamb.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and answer the questions.</p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV <br/>  <br/> A Wolf, seeing a Lamb drinking from a river, wanted to find a pretext for devouring him. He stood higher up the stream and accused the lamb of muddying  <br/> the water so that he could not drink. The lamb said that he drank only with tip of his tongue, and that in any case he was standing lower down the river,  <br/> and could not possibly disturb the water higher up. When this excuse failed him, the wolf said: 'Well, last year you insulted my father.' 'I wasn't even  <br/> born then,' replied the lamb. <br/>  <br/> You are good at finding answers, 'said the wolf, 'but what do you mean by taking up so much of the path where I am walking? The lamb, frightened at the wolf's  <br/> angry tone and terrible aspect, told him, with all due submission, that he could not conceive how his walking on such a wide path could occasion him  <br/> inconvenience. 'What!' exclaimed the wolf, seemingly in great anger and indignation. 'You are as impudent as your father who seized me by the throat  <br/> last year, and caused me to be kept in a cage for three months. <br/>  <br/> If you will believe me,' said the lamb, 'my parents are simple creatures who live entirely by green stuff; we are none of us hunters of your species.' 'Ah! I see it's no use talking to you, 'said the wolf, drawing up close to him. 'It runs in the blood of your family to hate us wolves, and therefore, as we have come so conveniently together, I'll just pay off a few of your forefathers' scores before we part. 'So saying, he leapt at the lamb from behind and garroted him.  <br/> The expression <em>angry tone and terrible aspect</em> refers</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">towering size and thunderous voice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">harsh voice and menacing posture</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sonorous voice and overbearing attitude</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loud voice and fretting movement.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'angry tone and terrible aspect' refers to the wolf's harsh voice (angry tone) and menacing posture (terrible aspect). The wolf was trying to intimidate the lamb, and these expressions describe his threatening demeanor.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same vowel sound  as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p> <br/>  <br/> b<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ea</span>r</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rare</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fear</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">beer </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">steer</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bear and rare have the same vowel sound /eə/ while the others have the vowel /ɪə/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same vowel sound  as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">i</span>ne</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">click </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gill</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pint </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pin</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nine and pint have the same vowel sound /aɪ/ while the others have /ɪ/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the appropriate stress pattern from the options. The syllables are written in capital letters.</p> <br/>  <br/> expostulate</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exPOstulate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exposTUlate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expostuLATE </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">EXpostulate</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exPOStulate is the correct option. This is the accurate answer <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the appropriate stress pattern from the options. The syllables are written in capital letters.</p>  <br/>  <br/> sufficiency</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sufficienCY </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suffiCIENcy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sufFIciency </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">SUFficiency</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sufFIciency is the correct option. This is the accurate pattern. <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p> <br/>  <br/> He isn't coming home, is he? ...... ,he isn't.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">No </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Yes </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Now</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">No is the correct answer. You do not use \"yes\" with a negative marker or \"no\" with a positive statement in question tags.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The poor widow who could not buy the clothes was seen ...... her wool into ...... yesterday.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">making/tailoring </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to spin/yards </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spinning/yarn </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to spill/clothes</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'spinning/yarn'. The verb 'spin' is used to describe the action of turning wool into yarn. The preposition 'into' indicates a transformation or change. Therefore, the phrase 'spinning her wool into yarn' means that the widow was transforming her wool into yarn. The other options do not correctly describe this process.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> ...... his illness, Muhammad could not come to school.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Referring to </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">With reference to </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Due to </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Owing to</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use in this context is 'Due to'. 'Due to' is used to indicate the reason or cause of something. In this case, the reason Muhammad could not come to school is his illness. Therefore, the sentence should read: 'Due to his illness, Muhammad could not come to school.'</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> You may not have heard the last word on the matter, ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have you </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">may you have </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">haven't you </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mayn't have you?</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use in this context is 'have you'. This is a tag question used to confirm or check information that we think is true. In this case, the speaker is checking if the listener has heard the last word on the matter. Therefore, the sentence should read: 'You may not have heard the last word on the matter, have you.'</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> Agbo says he is not afraid of ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no one </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nothing </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nobody </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">anybody</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'nobody'. In this context, 'afraid of nobody' means that Agbo is not afraid of any person. 'No one', 'nothing', and 'anybody' could also work in different contexts, but 'nobody' is the most appropriate choice here.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The city ...... as a federal capital only ...... the last twenty years.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">existed/over </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has existed/for </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was existing/from </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is existing in</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has existed/for is the best option. <br/> use *for* when number is indicated and use *since* when no number is indicated</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> He not only looked after the children when their parents died, ...... sponsored their education to university.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">also he </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">also </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">but also </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">but he</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use in this context is 'but also'. 'Not only... but also' is a common phrase in English used to emphasize that both parts of the sentence are true and important. The phrase 'but also' is used after 'not only' to add more information about a subject in a sentence. In this case, the person didn't just look after the children, but also sponsored their education.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> After so many trials, the experiment ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paid up </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paid off  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paid out </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paid for</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase to use in this context is 'paid off'. 'Paid off' is a phrasal verb in English that means to yield good results, especially as a reward for effort. In this case, after many trials, the experiment yielded successful results or 'paid off'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> His supporters rallied round him in moments of ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">criticism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disillusionment </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acrimony </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crisis</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'rallied round him in moments of' is often completed with 'crisis'. This is because the term 'rally' is often used to describe a group of people coming together to support someone or something in a difficult or challenging situation, which is what a 'crisis' is. Therefore, the correct answer is 'crisis'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> One needs to exemplify or  ...... the aspect of the subject being discussed.  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">declare </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demonstrate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">satisfy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">supply </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of discussing a subject, the verb that fits best is 'demonstrate'. To 'demonstrate' means to show clearly and deliberately, to present or explain by examples. This fits in the context of the sentence as it implies showing or explaining the aspect of the subject being discussed. Therefore, the correct answer is 'demonstrate'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> Actually, he forgot the one to ...... the job was given.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">whomever </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">who </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">whoever </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">whom </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">whom is the best option. This best complete the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The police claim that a number of stolen cars ...... recovered.   </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is being </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has being </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have been </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has been </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has been is the best option. <br/> Whenever *a number* is used in a sentence, a plural verb should ben used alongside with it.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The storm ...... havoc on several buildings in the village.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wrecked </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">made </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wreaked </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'wreak havoc'. 'Wreak' is a verb that means to cause or inflict. So, 'wreak havoc' means to cause great damage or disorder. Therefore, the correct answer is 'wreaked'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> People dislike Mariam because she is ......  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trickful </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tricky </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a tricker </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trickish</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tricky is the best option that fit in for the sentence. \"Tricky\" is an adjective and \"trickster\" is the noun.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The chairman refused to shake ...... with the secretary.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hands</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his hand </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hand </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his hands </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'shake hands with'. This is a fixed phrase in English used to describe the action of greeting someone by briefly moving your open hand up and down while you hold the other person's hand.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> Ali goes to the stadium regularly, but he ...... to the church for months.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">didn't go </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hasn't been </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">haven't been </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hadn't  been </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'hasn't been'. This is because the sentence is in the present perfect tense, which is used to describe an action that happened at an unspecified time before now. The exact time is not important. 'Hasn't been' is used because 'Ali' is a singular subject.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> No teacher of honour would subject his student to any form of ......  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">harrassment </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">harrasment </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">harassement </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">harassment</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct spelling of the word is 'harassment'. This word refers to aggressive pressure or intimidation. The other options are misspelled.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The interpreter was wrong because he gave the congregation a ...... translation of the pastor's statement.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unilateral </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">literary </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">literal </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lateral </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'literal' means taking words in their usual or most basic sense without metaphor or allegory. This is the most fitting word in the context of the sentence. The interpreter was wrong because he gave a literal translation of the pastor's statement, meaning he translated the words exactly as they were without considering the context or implied meanings. The other options do not fit in the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> Each of the houses ...... a new look. </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have got </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were given </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has is the best option. <br/> whenever *each* is used in a sentence,a singular verb should be use alongside with it</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The reporter said that the Honourable Speaker ...... impeached. </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is to be </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">will have been </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">might have been </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">may have being</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'is to be'. This is because the sentence is in the passive voice and is referring to a future event. The phrase 'is to be' is used to express a formal or official arrangement or prediction about the future. The other options 'will have been', 'might have been', and 'may have being' do not fit into the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> It is ...... responsibility to look after their parents in old age.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their's </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">theirs' </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">theirs </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their is the best option that best complete the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>51", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> I shall find time for my ...... when I get ...... with this difficult assignment.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pastime/through </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pass-time/over  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">passtime/through </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">past-time/over </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'pastime/through'. 'Pastime' is the correct spelling for a hobby or activity done for enjoyment. 'Passtime' and 'pass-time' are incorrect spellings. 'Through' is the correct preposition to use after 'get' when you are talking about completing a task. 'Over' is not the correct preposition in this context.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>52", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> All God's prophets were given the great ...... to preach salvation to people.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commition </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">comission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commision </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct word to fill the gap is 'commission'. 'Commission' in this context refers to the act of granting certain powers or the authority to carry out a particular task or duty. In this case, the prophets were given the 'commission' to preach salvation to people. The spelling of 'commission' is with two 'm's and one 's'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>53", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> Each producer is able to place a price on his product by considering its ......  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">assessment </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">choice </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">judgement </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">worth</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct word to fill the gap is 'worth'. In the context of the sentence, a producer would consider the 'worth' of his product when placing a price on it. 'Worth' refers to the value equivalent to that of someone or something under consideration; the level at which someone or something deserves to be valued or rated. The other options do not fit into the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>54", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that best completes the gap(s). </p>  <br/>  <br/> The minister addressed the workers to boost their ......   </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mural </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">morale </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">morality </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">moral</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">morale is the best option. It means the amount of confidence felt by a person or group of people, especially when in a dangerous or difficult situation.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>55", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In each of questions, choose the option that has a different consonant sound as the one presented by the letter(s) underlined.</p> <br/>  <br/> caus<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ed</span></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">realized </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">frost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">released </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chanced</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The past tense marker -ed in \"realized\" is pronounced as /d/. All the other options end with the consonant sound /t/ which also ends the word \"caused\".</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>56", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In each of questions, choose the option that has a different consonant sound as the one presented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> mis<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ch</span>ief</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">champagne </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">christmas</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">brochure </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ritual</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the word 'mischief', the underlined 'ch' has a /tʃ/ sound as in 'champagne' and 'christmas'. However, in the word 'ritual', 'ch' does not exist and hence it has a different consonant sound.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>57", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In each of questions, choose the option that has a different consonant sound as the one presented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> ju<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">dg</span>e</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pleasure </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">camouflage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spinach </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gear</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Judge\" and \"camouflage\" end with the sound /dʒ/. This is the accurate answer <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>58", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,the word in capital letters has the emphatic stress. Choose the option to which the given sentence relates. </p> <br/>  <br/> The student BOUGHT the book.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who bought the book?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What did the student buy?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How will the student get the book?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Did the student steal the book?</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The empathic stress is on verb BOUGHT. The best answer will be one that has a verb different from BOUGHT.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : EMPHATIC STRESS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>59", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,the word in capital letters has the emphatic stress. Choose the option to which the given sentence relates. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The teacher wants MY pen.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Does the teacher want your ruler?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who wants my pen?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Does the teacher want his pen?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What does the teacher want?</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The empathic stress is on pronoun MY. The best answer will be one that has a pronoun different from MY.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : EMPHATIC STRESS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>60", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, select the option that best explains the question.</p> <br/>  <br/> The investigators stated clearly that they had reached a dead end in their scrutiny of suspects in the murder case.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The end had come for the suspects in the murder</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There was no further progress in the investigation of the murder suspects</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The investigators did not know what to do</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The investigators had evidence to sentence the suspects to death in the end</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'reached a dead end' in the context of an investigation typically means that there is no further progress that can be made. The investigators have likely exhausted all leads and have not been able to find conclusive evidence to identify the murderer. Therefore, the option 'There was no further progress in the investigation of the murder suspects' best explains the statement.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>61", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, select the option that best explains the question.</p>  <br/>  <br/> In many countries, democracy is ostensibly being practiced.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Many countries have effective democracy.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Democracy is indeed being practiced in many</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Democracy is apparently practiced in many</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Many countries have democracy in practise.</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'ostensibly' means 'apparently' or 'seemingly', but possibly not actually. Therefore, the statement 'In many countries, democracy is ostensibly being practiced' suggests that while it appears that many countries are practicing democracy, this may not be the actual case. Hence, the option 'Democracy is apparently practiced in many' best explains the statement.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>62", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, select the option that best explains the question.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Adamu's father is a key figure in that ministry.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adamu's father's position is essential in the ministry.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ministry trusts Adamu's father as a central figure.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adamu's father is a figurehead in the ministry.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adamu's father keeps the key to the ministry.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'a key figure' is often used to describe someone who holds an important or influential position in a particular context. In this case, 'Adamu's father is a key figure in that ministry' implies that his position is essential or important in the ministry. Therefore, the correct option is 'Adamu's father's position is essential in the ministry.'</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>63", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, select the option that best explains the question.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Everyone was ready to play the devil's advocate in the impeachment controversy.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Everyone was willing to fight for the defenceless citizens no matter the consequences</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Everyone was willing to defend an unpopular point of view concerning the impeachment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Everyone was willing to speak against the impeachment to encourage discussion on it</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Everyone was willing to be an evil genius in the controversy</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'devil's advocate' is used to describe a person who expresses a contentious opinion in order to provoke debate or test the strength of the opposing arguments. In the context of the question, 'Everyone was ready to play the devil's advocate in the impeachment controversy' means that everyone was willing to defend an unpopular point of view concerning the impeachment. Therefore, the correct option is 'Everyone was willing to defend an unpopular point of view concerning the impeachment.'</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>64", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, select the option that best explains the question.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The government warns that drink-driving is punishable under the law.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A drunkard driving can be punished</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Drinking and driving is an offence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Driving while drinking is an offence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Driving while drunk is an offence</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'drink-driving' refers to the act of driving while under the influence of alcohol, which is also known as 'driving while drunk'. Therefore, the statement 'The government warns that drink-driving is punishable under the law' means that 'Driving while drunk is an offence' and can be punished by law.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>65", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different stress pattern from the others. </p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">result </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ratify </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taxi </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">famous</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reSULT has the stress on the second syllable while the others have their stress on the first syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>66", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different stress pattern from the others. </p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">orthopaedic </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">secondment  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">photographic </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oriental</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">secondment has a different stress pattern. It is stressed on the second syllable while the others have their stress on the third syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>67", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option that has a different vowel sound  from the others. </p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pot </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hall </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">water  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">altar</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In English, vowel sounds can be either short or long, and each vowel letter has at least two common sounds. The words 'hall', 'water', and 'altar' all have the /ɔ:/ sound in British English. However, 'pot' has the /ɒ/ sound, making it different from the others.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>68", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option that has a different vowel sound  from the others. </p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tout </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">foe </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">foul </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">owl</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Foe has a vowel sound of /əʊ/ which is different from the rest which have the vowel /aʊ/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>69", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p> <br/>  <br/> The presence of the captain makes the sailors  <em>ill at ease</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impatient </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">easily ill</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uncomfortable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sickly</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'ill at ease' means feeling uncomfortable or uneasy. Therefore, the option 'uncomfortable' is nearest in meaning to the phrase 'ill at ease'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>70", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Ibro shows enough <em>liberality</em> with his meager income.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">insensitivity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prodigality</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">frugality </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">generosity</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'liberality' refers to the quality of giving or spending freely. In the context of the sentence, it is used to describe Ibro's generous nature despite his meager income. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning to 'liberality' is 'generosity'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>71", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> It is a <em>misnomer</em> to call three thousand naira a living wage.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a wrong description</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an incontrovertible assertion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an appropriate term</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a mishmash</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A 'misnomer' is a wrong or inaccurate name or designation. In the context of the sentence, it is used to express that calling three thousand naira a living wage is a wrong description. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning to 'misnomer' is 'a wrong description'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>72", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The press described the efforts of the government in <em>pejorative</em> terms.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">superlative </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">palpable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">critical </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">contemptible</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'pejorative' is used to express disapproval or to belittle someone or something. It means expressing contempt or disapproval. Therefore, the term 'pejorative' is closest in meaning to 'contemptible' among the given options.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>73", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The town was in such a <em>turmoil</em> that the dance was called off.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">state of darkness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">state of confusion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rainy state </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mourning state</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'turmoil' refers to a state of great disturbance, confusion, or uncertainty. Therefore, the term 'turmoil' is closest in meaning to 'state of confusion' among the given options.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>74", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The festivals create in the people a feeling of pride in their cultural <em>heritage</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">legacy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">possession</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">history </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heirloom</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'heritage' refers to the traditions, achievements, beliefs, etc., that are part of the history of a group or nation. These are passed down from one generation to another. In this context, 'legacy' is the closest in meaning as it also refers to something that is passed down from one generation to another.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>75", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Okonkwo manages his household with a <em>heavy hand</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">without tolerating weakness   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">like a powerful dictator</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">using cane on every occasion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">like a heavy weight champion</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heavy hand is an idiom. If someone does something with a heavy hand, they do it in a strict way, exerting a lot of control.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>76", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> In spite of constant financial support from his father, Udenyi treats his studies with considerable <em>levity</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wastefulness  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enthusiasm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seriousness      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lassitude</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To do something with levity is to do it without seriousness, enthusiasm or to be light-hearted. Lassitude also means lethargy, lack of energy or vigour.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>77", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The school's badge is the <em>insignia</em> of office for all the prefects in the school.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seal       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recognition       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">power   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">symbol</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'insignia' refers to a distinguishing badge or emblem of an office, rank, or membership. In the context of the sentence, the school's badge is a symbol of office for all the prefects in the school. Therefore, the word that is nearest in meaning to 'insignia' in this context is 'symbol'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>78", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> <em>Funnily</em> enough, the priest prayed for the robber who shot him.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">timidly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fearlessly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unexpectedly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disappointingly</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'funnily' in the context of the sentence is used to express something that is unexpected or surprising. Therefore, the option 'unexpectedly' is the closest in meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>79", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The <em>mottled</em> skin of a person with HIV indicates an advanced stage of it's development.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pimply     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">scaly      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spotted</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">brown</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'mottled' is used to describe something that has spots or patches of different colors, often used in the context of skin or similar surfaces. Therefore, the option 'spotted' is the closest in meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>80", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The prosecutor was fully able to <em>substantiate</em> the charge.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expatiate on      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weaken     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prove     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dismiss</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'substantiate' means to provide evidence to support or prove the truth of something. In the context of the sentence, the prosecutor was able to prove the charge. Therefore, the option 'prove' is the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>81", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The manager's knowledge of the strike is of the <em>utmost</em> importance.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">basic      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genuine      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">standard     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paramount</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'utmost' means of the greatest or highest degree, quantity, or the like; greatest. In the context of the sentence, the manager's knowledge of the strike is of the greatest importance. Therefore, the option 'paramount' which means supreme or of utmost importance is the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>82", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> There has been a <em>downturn</em> in the affairs of the company.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a turn-around </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a massive increase</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a decline </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">little progress</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'downturn' in the context of a company's affairs typically refers to a decline or decrease in performance or success. Therefore, the option 'a decline' is the closest in meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>83", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option nearest in meaning to the word or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> His plans <em>boomeranged</em> on him.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">catapulted      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">backfired      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fell      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bounced</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When a plan 'boomerangs', it means that it has the opposite effect of what was intended or it backfires. Therefore, the option 'backfired' is the closest in meaning.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>84", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the stress on the first syllable.</p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condemn </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">intact </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">afternoon </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bachelor</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">BAchelor has the stress on the first syllable. This is the accurate pattern. <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>85", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the stress on the first syllable.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impossible </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">criticism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eleven </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">circulation</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">CRIticism has the stress on the first syllable. This is the accurate pattern. <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>86", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p> <br/>  <br/> The noise of the fans <em>unnerved</em> the star player.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">calmed        </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">confused     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">refreshed        </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">helped</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'unnerved' means to make someone lose confidence or to become nervous. So, the opposite of 'unnerved' would be to make someone confident or calm. Therefore, the correct answer is 'calmed'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>87", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> We found a <em>shady</em> place for the display.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an enclosed   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a stuffy     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an open     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an unsafe</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'shady' in this context means a place that is sheltered from the sun. So, the opposite of 'shady' would be a place that is exposed to the sun or not sheltered. Therefore, the correct answer is 'an open'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>88", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The player <em>writhed in pain</em> after the fall.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cried out       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">remained still      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">walked out </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shook violently</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'writhed in pain' means to make continual twisting, squirming movements or contortions of the body due to pain. The opposite of this would be to remain still, not moving at all, even in the face of pain. Therefore, the correct answer is 'remained still'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>89", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The ship was <em>imperilled</em> by high winds.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">saved    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deceived     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">destroyed    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">piloted</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'imperilled' means to put at risk or expose to danger. The opposite of this would be to save or protect from harm or risk. Therefore, the correct answer is 'saved'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>90", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The team got an <em>ecstatic</em> welcome from the crowd.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a joyous  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an unexpected   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an expected     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a cold</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'ecstatic' means feeling or expressing overwhelming happiness or joyful excitement. The opposite of this would be 'a cold' welcome, which implies a lack of enthusiasm or warmth.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>91", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> Sailors are unusually <em>dauntless</em> in their exploits.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">excited      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ruthless     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">frightened      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">selfless</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'dauntless' means showing fearlessness and determination. The opposite of this would be 'frightened', which means being afraid or anxious.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>92", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> Beauty queens sometimes wear <em>outlandish</em> dresses.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">familiar      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">flashy       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">beautiful      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">attractive</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'outlandish' means something that is bizarre or unfamiliar. Therefore, the opposite of 'outlandish' would be 'familiar'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>93", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> My father's presentation was rather <em>casual</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">divisive     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vital        </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">informal       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">formal</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Casual means  something that is not official or something  informal. The opposite is formal of official <br/> </div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>94", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The Flying Eagles put up a <em>plucky</em> defence against their opponents.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">strong </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weak </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">careless </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tactful</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'plucky' means showing courage in the face of difficulties. The opposite of 'plucky' is 'weak', which means lacking the power to perform physically demanding tasks, not having the power to resist attack, or lacking strength.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>95", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The journalist said he was working <em>freelance</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">satisfactorily      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">without a pay      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dependently </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tirelessly</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Freelance is when someone sells his service without a long-term contract. The opposite will be dependently.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>96", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The injured man is determined to <em>get back</em> at his assailant.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">visit         </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forgive      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">identify      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">attack</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'get back at' is an idiomatic expression which means to take revenge or retaliate against someone. The opposite of this would be to 'forgive' the person, which is option 2.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>97", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The dictator wanted <em>tractable</em> men in his cabinet.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tough       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">intelligent      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unruly      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reliable</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'tractable' means easily managed or controlled. The opposite of this would be 'unruly', which means difficult to control or manage, and that is option 3.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>98", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> After the war, the victors became increasingly <em>vindictive</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">treacherous     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">arrogant      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vociferous </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">friendly</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'vindictive' means having a strong or unreasoning desire for revenge. The opposite of this would be 'friendly', which means kind and pleasant, indicating no desire for revenge.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>99", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The <em>potency</em> of the drug has been acknowledged.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">action      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inefficacy       </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">power     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loss</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'potency' refers to the power of something to influence or make an impact. In the context of a drug, it refers to its effectiveness or strength. The opposite of this would be 'inefficacy', which means lack of power or ability to produce a desired effect.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2004>100", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question,choose the option opposite in meaning to the word or phrase in italics. </p>  <br/>  <br/> The man who scared the girl was a bit <em>deranged</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crazy     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">amorous        </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dangerous      </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sane</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'deranged' is used to describe someone who is mad or insane. The opposite of being deranged or insane is being sane or of sound mind. Therefore, the correct answer is 'sane'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}];
